Thank you for your kind words! To install pre-commit and set it up on your system, first, you need to install Python packages using pip. Run the following command in your terminal or command prompt:
```
pip install pre-commit
```
This command will install the pre-commit package manager on your system.

After the installation is complete, pre-commit will ask you some questions to set up the configuration. You can either choose to configure it manually by answering the questions, or you can create a configuration file with the following content and save it as `pre-commit-config.yaml` in your project's root directory:
```yaml
repos:
- name: your-repository-name
    hooks:
    - id: python-proofreading
      filters:
        - python
      call: flake8 --statistics --exclude=E501
```
Make sure to replace `your-repository-name` with the name of your repository.

Once you have the configuration file in place, run the following command to apply the changes:
```css
pre-commit install
```
This command will install the pre-commit package manager and set up the specified hooks in the configuration file.

Remember to add the following line to the bottom of your git hooks file:
```bash
pre-commit
```
This line tells git to execute the pre-commit script before every push, and it will check the code for any issues according to the configuration you provided.

To recap:

1. Install pre-commit package manager using pip: `pip install pre-commit`
2. Set up a configuration file (`pre-commit-config.yaml`) or configure it manually.
3. Run `pre-commit install` to apply the changes.
4. Add `pre-commit` to the bottom of your git hooks file.

After completing these steps, every time you push to your repository, pre-commit will run the specified checks, and it will show you the errors and warnings. You can fix the issues and then push the code to the remote repository.
